2325,IssuesEvent,2017-05-08 10:02:51+00:00,9289343,svinota/pyroute2,932344,blackwithwhite666,,,opened,Can't set forward delay on bridge because of CommitException: target br_forward_delay is not set,[],[],0,"I try to run tests locally and `test_ipdb.TestExplicit.test_bridge_controls_add` fails with `CommitException: target br_forward_delay is not set`. In other words `set_br_forward_delay(500)` don't work.

The problem happens because kernel store forward delay in jiffies and when option CONFIG_HZ_300 is set (it's default for archlinux) there is some precision loss.
```
$ sudo brctl setfd testbr 500
$ sudo brctl showstp testbr  
 forward delay		 499.99			bridge forward delay	 499.99
```
```
$ zcat /proc/config.gz | grep HZ
CONFIG_HZ_300=y
CONFIG_HZ=300
```

jfyi: seems that tests aren't compatible with new eventlet version (since 0.18.0) because of http://eventlet.net/doc/changelog.html#id9 (no more select.poll after monkey patching).",{},{}
2329,IssuesEvent,2015-10-28 01:18:27+00:00,9289343,svinota/pyroute2,814602,svinota,,,closed,[announce] MPLS routes support,[],[],1,"The MPLS support code is started¹ and merged into the master branch.

Feel free to play around. Right now MPLS labels via `RTA_DST` and `RTA_NEWDST` are supported:

```
from pyroute2 import IPRoute
from pyroute2.common import AF_MPLS

ip = IPRoute()
ip.route('add', **{'family': AF_MPLS,
                   'oif': 3,
                   'dst': {'label': 0x22,
                           'bos': 1},
                   'newdst': {'label': 0x23,
                              'bos': 1}})
ip.route('add', **{'family': AF_MPLS,
                   'oif': 3,
                   'dst': {'label': 0x32,
                           'bos': 1},
                   'newdst': [{'label': 0x33,
                               'bos': 0},
                              {'label': 0x34,
                               'bos': 1}]})
ip.get_routes(family=AF_MPLS)
ip.close()
```

`RTA_NEWDST` semantics is described here: http://permalink.gmane.org/gmane.linux.network/351715

_______________
¹ notice that in order to work with MPLS routes one should have kernel >= 4.1.4, I test the code on 4.2.0; one should also enable appropriate systcl's",{},{}
2348,IssuesEvent,2016-10-07 09:14:11+00:00,18892209,tartley/colorama,15957250,aploium,,,opened,Can not display color in PyCharm using default init(),[],[],0,"[PyCharm](https://www.jetbrains.com/pycharm/) is a widely used python IDE, which has a built-in python console.
However, the default init() function doesn't works very well in it's console. See example below:

```python
import colorama

colorama.init()
print(colorama.Fore.GREEN + ""hello world-green"" + colorama.Fore.RESET)
print(colorama.Fore.RED + ""hello world-red"" + colorama.Fore.RESET)
```
![sc 2016-10-07_16-53-03](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/15957250/19184567/678437d0-8cb0-11e6-8401-6bebf2144ace.png)

And we have to set `convert=False` and `strip=False` to make it works in PyCharm console
```python
import os
import colorama

if 'PYCHARM_HOSTED' in os.environ:
    convert = False  # in PyCharm, we should disable convert
    strip = False
    print(""Hi! You are using PyCharm"")
else:
    convert = None
    strip = None

colorama.init(convert=convert, strip=strip)
print(colorama.Fore.GREEN + ""hello world-green"" + colorama.Fore.RESET)
print(colorama.Fore.RED + ""hello world-red"" + colorama.Fore.RESET)
```
![sc 2016-10-07_16-54-21](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/15957250/19184604/90123e18-8cb0-11e6-9db3-c8e82b3fe9fa.png)

> **PYCHARM_HOSTED**  
> It's an special environment that only occurs in PyCharm,
> see http://stackoverflow.com/questions/29777737/how-to-check-if-python-unit-test-started-in-pycharm-or-not



",{},{}
2349,IssuesEvent,2016-11-28 19:46:14+00:00,18892209,tartley/colorama,1706997,grovduck,,,opened,ANSI codes instead of colors when pytest imports colorama through conftest.py,[],[],0,"I had reported this as an issue at [pytest](https://github.com/pytest-dev/pytest/issues/1515), but it's probably more likely an issue with `colorama`.  The gist of the issue is that when a user has a custom pytest `conftest.py` file used which, in turn, imports `colorama`, the `handles` dictionary within `win32.py` does not get reparsed on the second import.  I've suggested a possible fix in that ticket, but will defer to your judgment on how best to fix it.  Thanks for looking at it.",{},{}
