3321,IssuesEvent,2016-03-21 17:28:59+00:00,8292338,ultrabug/py3status,474389,ultrabug,,,closed,RFC : module_group / scroll_group,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/ultrabug/py3status/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/ultrabug/py3status/labels/question', 'name': 'question', 'color': 'cc317c'}]",[],4,"**Dear py3status users, tell us what you think !**

As discussed in PR #155 with @tjaartvdwalt and @pydsigner.

A `scroll_group` or `module_group` whatever the name handled by py3status would allow users to **group multiple modules together** and switch between them using the mouse scroll buttons (4 and 5) !

This way users could still benefit from click events on mouse buttons 1, 2 and 3 on each module. My first idea would give something like this on i3status.conf for your use case (I need to use two different module instance _first_ and wlan0 to get them work on the same i3status output) :

````
wireless _first_ {
	format_down = ""W""
	format_up = ""%ip""
	scroll_group = 1
}

wireless wlan0 {
	format_down = ""W""
	format_up = ""%essid""
	scroll_group = 1
}
````

This would make py3status group the two outputs together and display one or the other on mouse scroll automatically.

What's interesting with this is that this would work with every module available and users could then group and *toggle* whatever modules they want together with a single line config.

Of course, the scroll_group itself would be configurable (we could even want it to scroll each module automatically at a given interval !)",{},{}
3330,IssuesEvent,2017-06-08 12:16:35+00:00,8292338,ultrabug/py3status,1177900,maximbaz,,,opened,Module 'net_rate' should respect 'unit' with 'hide_if_zero = true' and in thresholds,[],[],0,"Set the following config:

```
net_rate {
  format = '[\?color=total {total}]'
  thresholds = {'total': [(0, 'good'), (1048576, 'degraded'), (10485760, 'bad')]} # 1 MB/s, 10 MB/s
  hide_if_zero = true
  unit = 'MB/s'
}
```

----------------

1. Observe that even though the `hide_if_zero = true`, the module prints `0.0 MB/s`. This happens because the code is using the absolute rate, in bytes, not in the unit defined:

```
# if there is no rate - show last active interface, or hide
if deltas[interface]['total'] == 0:    <-------------- here
    interface = self.last_interface
    hide = self.hide_if_zero
```

The value of `deltas[interface]['total']` is maybe `309.25828642304896` (bytes) which is non-zero.

A naive fix to format with the units would be like this:

```
# if there is no rate - show last active interface, or hide
total, _ = self.py3.format_units(deltas[interface]['total'], unit=self.unit, si=self.si_units)
if total == 0:
    interface = self.last_interface
    hide = self.hide_if_zero
```

However it doesn't help, because now the total contains `0.000309` for the same value, and it is still non-zero. The reason we see `0.0 MB/s` in the output is because the value `0.000309` is then additionally formatted with the formatter `{value:.1f}`.

The desired behavior is to synchronize what I see in the bar (`0.0 MB/s`) with the behavior of `hide_if_zero = true`, so that I don't ever see module in the bar with the value of `0.0 MB/s`.

-----------

2. Notice how I had to define thresholds:

```
thresholds = {'total': [(0, 'good'), (1048576, 'degraded'), (10485760, 'bad')]} # 1 MB/s, 10 MB/s
```

Less important, but ideally this would also respect the unit and allow me to set thresholds in megabytes, like this:


```
thresholds = {'total': [(0, 'good'), (1, 'degraded'), (10, 'bad')]} # 1 MB/s, 10 MB/s
unit = 'MB/s'
```",{},{}
