4593,IssuesEvent,2017-12-24 16:15:44+00:00,58594760,johnwheeler/flask-ask,579418,pavelanni,,,opened,Storing Flask-Ask objects in DynamoDB,[],[],0,"It's not actually a Flask-Ask issue, but something to be aware of if you are going to work with DynamoDB. I finally found a solution that I want to share in case somebody else happens to see similar errors. Here is my situation: 

I have a dictionary in my app, something like `user_state = {'a': [1, 2], 'b': [2, 3], 'c': [3, 4]}`. I want to store it in my DynamoDB table. When I call `table.update_item()` from `boto3` I get a long list of nasty error messages from somewhere deep in the `copy` module of the standard library. Like this:

```
. . .
  File ""/home/pavel/anaconda3/lib/python3.6/copy.py"", line 150, in deepcopy
    y = copier(x, memo)
  File ""/home/pavel/anaconda3/lib/python3.6/copy.py"", line 240, in _deepcopy_dict
    y[deepcopy(key, memo)] = deepcopy(value, memo)
  File ""/home/pavel/anaconda3/lib/python3.6/copy.py"", line 150, in deepcopy
    y = copier(x, memo)
  File ""/home/pavel/anaconda3/lib/python3.6/copy.py"", line 240, in _deepcopy_dict
    y[deepcopy(key, memo)] = deepcopy(value, memo)
  File ""/home/pavel/anaconda3/lib/python3.6/copy.py"", line 169, in deepcopy
    rv = reductor(4)
TypeError: 'NoneType' object is not callable
```
I tried to print out the dict before storing it and it looks just like a normal dict. I tried to put the same dict literally in the code and it stored without any problems. Without much hope, I printed out the type of this dict and what did I see?
```
type(user_state) is <class 'flask_ask.models._Field'>
```
So when I added 
```
user_state = dict(user_state)
```
it started to work perfectly fine!

So, again, it's not something that needs to be fixed in Flask-Ask, but rather something to be aware of, if you work with DynamoDB database. I don't know it may appear somewhere else.",{},{}
