4733,IssuesEvent,2016-05-24 17:58:55+00:00,32184901,tomduck/pandoc-fignos,11214837,derekmerck,,,opened,Proposal:  Support inter-figure references in captions,[],[],0,"Hi @tomduck -- thanks so much for contributing these filters to the community; I use your *nos filters for academic writing all the time!

It currently appears to be impossible to use an `{@fig:my_fig}` reference inside the caption of a tracked figure to reference another one (or itself?).  I can imagine why this kind of recursion would be a pain to support, but I am surprisingly often missing this functionality.  How hard would it be to implement?",{},{}
4784,IssuesEvent,2017-07-23 06:58:51+00:00,30582779,warner/magic-wormhole,27146,warner,,,closed,client should reject non-numeric nameplates in the wormhole code,[],[],0,"Looking at the server, I'm seeing a few transfers fail because one side used a nameplate of ""6"" and the other side used "" 6"" (with a leading space). As far as the server knows, these are both completely legitimate (but unrelated) nameplates, and the two clients will hang forever waiting for the other one to show up.

I assume it's just a basic cut-and-paste failure (they selected one character too many), but the client should really reject a leading space in the wormhole code. Likewise I've seen a few indications of other words being used as the nameplate (mostly ""asdf"" or ""foo"", so not from a real code, but I assume some folks will hear ""four-purple-sausages"" instead of ""4-purple-sausages"" and type in a non-numeric nameplate that way).

So the task is to change the client's nameplate-entry code to reject anything that isn't strictly `/\d+/`, with a message about how wormhole codes start with digits.",{},{}
4811,IssuesEvent,2015-03-01 13:43:18+00:00,15857755,DenisCarriere/geocoder,803596,Steindi01,,,opened,"Error handling in def _get_bbox(self, south, west, north, east):",[],[],0,"The method ```def _get_bbox(self, south, west, north, east):``` in ```base.py``` sometimes raises an error like:

```python
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""C:\Python27\lib\site-packages\geocoder\api.py"", line 114, in google
    return get(location, provider='google', **kwargs)
  File ""C:\Python27\lib\site-packages\geocoder\api.py"", line 100, in get
