4921,IssuesEvent,2017-09-15 07:02:35+00:00,97002861,ljvmiranda921/pyswarms,12949683,ljvmiranda921,,,opened,Add assertions() in search methods,"[{'id': 654551006, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/ljvmiranda921/pyswarms/labels/first-timers-only', 'name': 'first-timers-only', 'color': 'f9d0c4', 'default': False}, {'id': 645411972, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/ljvmiranda921/pyswarms/labels/help%20wanted', 'name': 'help wanted', 'color': '128A0C', 'default': True}]",[],0,"Thanks to Siobhan, we're now able to implement hyperparameter search tools such as `GridSearch` and `RandomSearch`. These are awesome implementations, but we can maximize its robustness by adding an `assertions()` method in our classes. Would you like to try?

## What you'll do 
Simply put, you will just add an `assertions()` method in the `SearchBase` class. This should contain various
checks when instantiating any class that inherits from it. You can check the docstrings for each class and create a proper method call for it. 

If you want to check previous implementations, see the `SwarmBase.assertions` method, and check how it is being implemented in `GlobalBestPSO` (it is not called explicitly because it just inherits from the base) or in `LocalBestPSO` (additional lines of code were added after calling the `super()` because of extra attributes).

## Go the extra mile?
If you want to go the extra mile, you can add tests to check for edge cases and see if your assertions are working when passed with an invalid input (maybe an invalid type, out-of-bounds, etc.). For this, you just need to add an `Instantiation` class in the `test.utils.search.test_gridsearch` and `test.utils.search.test_randomsearch` modules. 

Again, if you want a template, you can check the `Instantiation` classes in `test.optimizers.test_global_best` and others. Notice how we try to feed the class with invalid arguments/edge cases and have the unit test capture them. It's a very fun activity!

If you wish to take this on, then feel free to drop a comment here! I'd be glad to help you!",{},{}
4924,IssuesEvent,2018-08-12 15:25:45+00:00,97002861,ljvmiranda921/pyswarms,39431903,whzup,,,opened,Add the `hypothesis` module to the test suite,"[{'id': 961920752, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWw5NjE5MjA3NTI=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/ljvmiranda921/pyswarms/labels/unit%20tests', 'name': 'unit tests', 'color': 'f9e22f', 'default': False}, {'id': 1016681578, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWwxMDE2NjgxNTc4', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/ljvmiranda921/pyswarms/labels/v.0.4.0', 'name': 'v.0.4.0', 'color': 'c2e0c6', 'default': False}]","[{'login': 'whzup', 'id': 39431903, 'node_id': 'MDQ6VXNlcjM5NDMxOTAz', 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars3.githubusercontent.com/u/39431903?v=4', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/whzup', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/whzup', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/whzup/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/whzup/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/whzup/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/whzup/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/whzup/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/whzup/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/whzup/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/whzup/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/whzup/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",0,"Since we had some issues with testing in the past, I propose that we include the [`hypothesis` module for Python](https://github.com/HypothesisWorks/hypothesis/tree/master/hypothesis-python) into our test suite. Side by side with the `pytest` module we're already running as it is [compatible with `pytest`](https://hypothesis.readthedocs.io/en/latest/supported.html). The `hypothesis` module allows us to cover a broader range in our parametrization and checks edge cases. As they say it on their page:
 > It lets you write tests which are parametrized by a source of examples, and then generates simple and comprehensible examples that make your tests fail. This lets you find more bugs in your code with less work.

It is quite powerful and might help us in finding bugs earlier.",{},{}
