5784,IssuesEvent,2018-02-17 01:00:22+00:00,20556335,fmfn/BayesianOptimization,3453650,spadavec,,,opened,Integrating a MLP with BO,[],[],0,"Forgive my ignorance (as I am relatively new to this) but I would like to be able to use this codebase to efficient search 'chemical' space (searching vector space learned via an autoencoder), with a target function that is a multi-layer perceptron that returns estimates of a molecular property (built on a different sequential model) that I want to minimize. In this case, then, I have a few questions: 

1) Wouldn't it be best to supply an `init_points` equal to the number of training data points that I used to train my other MLP, instead of the traditional 2 or 3? 

2) in the example code: 
```python
 bo.maximize(init_points=2, n_iter=0, acq='ucb', kappa=5)
```
Does the `bo.maximize` refer to the maximizing of the expected y-value of your target function, or does it maximize whatever your acquisition function? In my case, I'd like to minimize the output of the target function. ",{},{}
5796,IssuesEvent,2016-11-11 00:28:29+00:00,67307930,indygreg/python-zstandard,4776584,djih,,,opened,Saving and loading the training dict_data,[],[],0,"After we train on a sample, we want to be able to save the dict_data to a binary file so we can load and re-use it across different applications. It seems like the ZstdCompressionDict object is not pickle-able or serializable. We don't want to have to re-train on a sample every time we want to use zstd.

My current work-around is to use the zstd command line tool to generate the dictionary binary, and then load it into python. The issue with that is the command line program has its own limitations, such as this: https://github.com/facebook/zstd/issues/373#issuecomment-259847707",{},{}
