7118,IssuesEvent,2017-12-22 04:36:30+00:00,34864402,apache/incubator-mxnet,5545640,eric-haibin-lin,47359,apache,opened,row_sparse ndarray + 0 should not return dense ndarray,"[{'id': 707556574, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/apache/incubator-mxnet/labels/Operator', 'name': 'Operator', 'color': 'fbca04', 'default': False}, {'id': 720179133, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/apache/incubator-mxnet/labels/Sparse', 'name': 'Sparse', 'color': '7ab4ef', 'default': False}]",[],0,"Currently `nd._plus_scalar(row_sparse, 0)` and `nd._minus_scalar(row_sparse, 0)` return dense NDArray. Instead it can return a row-sparse NDArray directly. This is causing extra conversions when checkpointing the model, as `module.get_params` calls [this](https://github.com/apache/incubator-mxnet/blob/master/python/mxnet/module/executor_group.py#L414-L416) which in turn calls `nd._plus_scalar(row_sparse, 0)`. 
To support sparse ndarray output for these two operators we just need to update the infer storage logic [here](https://github.com/apache/incubator-mxnet/blob/05047ad8fee4e8ee63ae2b7f96e7e9c7684fa4a0/src/operator/tensor/elemwise_binary_scalar_op_basic.cc#L61-L66)
",{},{}
7128,IssuesEvent,2017-09-30 11:05:50+00:00,34864402,apache/incubator-mxnet,771744,yajiedesign,47359,apache,closed,problem in example/image-classification/predict-cpp/image-classification-predict.cc,[],[],1,"I'm using the MXNET in C++ API refer to the example in example/image-classification/predict-cpp/image-classification-predict.cc. I have one question in the `GetImageFile` function.

The code as follow:
```
for (int i = 0; i < im.rows; i++) {
        uchar* data = im.ptr<uchar>(i);

        for (int j = 0; j < im.cols; j++) {
            if (mean_data) {
                mean_r = *mean_data;
                if (channels > 1) {
                    mean_g = *(mean_data + size / 3);
                    mean_b = *(mean_data + size / 3 * 2);
                }
               mean_data++;
            }
            if (channels > 1) {
                *ptr_image_g++ = static_cast<mx_float>(*data++) - mean_g;
                *ptr_image_b++ = static_cast<mx_float>(*data++) - mean_b;
            }

            *ptr_image_r++ = static_cast<mx_float>(*data++) - mean_r;;
        }
    }
```
My question is:
Is the order wrong when get the channels from the image matrix? As I know, the order of the channels is BGR in OpenCV.
```
                *ptr_image_g++ = static_cast<mx_float>(*data++) - mean_g;
                *ptr_image_b++ = static_cast<mx_float>(*data++) - mean_b;
```

",{},{}
