7831,IssuesEvent,2017-03-12 14:32:48+00:00,9155431,spotify/annoy,1029874,pommedeterresautee,251374,spotify,opened,New set_seed not always producing consistent results,[],[],0,"I was trying to have reproductible results with Annoy and discovered the `set_seed` feature has been added merged very recently (https://github.com/spotify/annoy/commit/2de9fd3eee45ef83b1e8d6ed372edc370e503a5c).

In my tests, when I compare several times the retrieval for 2 models based on a large dataset (like 1 million random vectors) of 300d for instance, sometimes I get the same results, sometimes not.
Seems to happen more when the dataset is large that when it is small and dimensions > 100.
FYI results are always perfectly exact with 1000 vectors and 50d (tried many times).

When the test is failing, results retrieved from both models are ""very similar"" but with the same seed I expect exactly the same resutls. Seems to be an issue with `set_seed` only.

Any idea @yonromai @erikbern ?

FYI my code is in Scala, just calling the C++ with JNI, nothing done in between.

```scala
  val seed = 42
  Random.setSeed(seed)
  val numberOfVectors = 1000000
  val dimensions = 300
  val trees = 30
  val vectors = Array.fill(numberOfVectors)(Array.fill(dimensions)(Random.nextGaussian().toFloat)).zipWithIndex

  val annoy1 = AnnoyInstance(new File(""""), dimensions, seed = seed, loadModel = false, verbose = true)
  for ((vector, index) ← vectors) {
    annoy1.addItem(index, vector)
  }
  annoy1.build(trees)
  val annoy2 = AnnoyInstance(new File(""""), dimensions, seed = seed, loadModel = false, verbose = true)
  for ((vector, index) ← vectors) {
    annoy2.addItem(index, vector)
  }
  annoy2.build(trees)
  assert(annoy1.getNItems == numberOfVectors)
  assert(annoy2.getNItems == numberOfVectors)
  for (_ ← 1 to 500) {
    val elementToTest = Random.nextInt(numberOfVectors)
    assert(annoy1.getNnsByItem(elementToTest, 100).sameElements(annoy2.getNnsByItem(elementToTest, 100)))
  }
```",{},{}
7844,IssuesEvent,2017-04-12 14:04:43+00:00,9155431,spotify/annoy,106586,bartolsthoorn,251374,spotify,opened,Reducing RAM with float16?,[],[],0,"Hi, this is more a question than an issue :smile: is it possible to reduce the RAM while creating the index by setting `type='float16'` on my numpy arrays?

```python
f = 40
t = AnnoyIndex(f)  # Length of item vector that will be indexed
for i in xrange(1000):
    v = [random.gauss(0, 1) for z in xrange(f)]
    t.add_item(i, np.array(v, dtype='float16'))
```
I am dealing with ~40M vectors and I have 8GB of RAM, and now I'm hitting the swap at the end a bit.",{},{}
7853,IssuesEvent,2015-08-06 11:31:15+00:00,9155431,spotify/annoy,1027979,erikbern,251374,spotify,closed,can't install with Python3,[],[],13,"Hi. Newbie to Github here. Thanks for this wonderful piece of software.

I think I've a small bug in the install with Python 3:
```
(annoy)horace89@horace89:~/tst1/annoy$ python -V
Python 3.4.0
(annoy)horace89@horace89:~/tst1/annoy$ pip install annoy              
Collecting annoy
  Using cached annoy-1.4.1.tar.gz
    Complete output from command python setup.py egg_info:
    Traceback (most recent call last):
      File ""<string>"", line 20, in <module>
      File ""/tmp/pip-build-ygnacgga/annoy/setup.py"", line 34, in <module>
        long_description = readme_note + fobj.read()
      File ""/home/horace89/.virtualenvs/annoy/lib/python3.4/encodings/ascii.py"", line 26, in decode
        return codecs.ascii_decode(input, self.errors)[0]
    UnicodeDecodeError: 'ascii' codec can't decode byte 0xe2 in position 3767: ordinal not in range(128)
```

If I build a virtualenv with Python2.7, the error disappears and the build is ok.
If I use a virtualenv with Python3.4 and if I edit the setup.py file with (I comment out fobj.read()) :
```with open('README.rst') as fobj:
long_description = readme_note #+ fobj.read()```
, the error disappears and the build is ok.
So I think, there's an issue with the utf-8 encoding.",{},{}
7897,IssuesEvent,2015-08-19 00:04:34+00:00,5888353,spotify/luigi,5551175,nickthorpe,251374,spotify,opened,Issues Opening Local Target as Output,[],[],0,"When attempting to open and write to output with the following syntax (paper_output = self.output().open('w')) no file is created following the run (on AWS EC2 instance... running Ubuntu). This was the syntax given in the documentation here: http://luigi.readthedocs.org/en/stable/tasks.html (see Task.run)

The same syntax works running on Windows 10. When the line was changed to the following syntax (        with self.output().open('w') as aminer_paper_output:) the output was successfully created. ",{},{}
7928,IssuesEvent,2016-08-22 06:18:36+00:00,5888353,spotify/luigi,9068118,jnthm,251374,spotify,closed,No control over tuning of luigi-server.log.,[],[],4,"We are starting to run thousands of luigi tasks every day at Ooyala, and in our staging environment, we have noticed that the luigi-server.log ends up taking about a gigabyte of space everyday. Most of the traffic seems to be generated from tornado.access package. We haven't figured out a way to control logging level of luigi-server.log from a logging config file. 

