8995,IssuesEvent,2016-11-10 20:32:48+00:00,2640766,astropy/photutils,346587,eteq,847984,astropy,opened,Add quality-of-fit information to the photometry fit outputs,"[{'id': 100230801, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/astropy/photutils/labels/psf', 'name': 'psf', 'color': 'c5def5', 'default': False}]",[],0,"This overlaps somewhat with #443, but is somewhat distinct - the psf photometry machinery should output quality-of-fit information.  There are two particular things that I think might be relatively easy to do now:

1. A chi (or chi-squared) for the fit.  This could be just a directly computed chi-squared from the model, but *might* be best done to match the ALLSTAR implementation of `chi`... That may or may not be the same as a textbook `sqrt(chi-squared)`...  I'm not sure but it's probably written down somewhere?  @mirca have you you seen anything about this?
2. Information from the fitter itself.  For `LevMarLSQFitter` I'm thinking about the `fitter.fit_info['ierr']` or `fitter.fit_info['message']`.  I think we *don't* necessarily want the message by default (because that could dominate the size of the output table), but maybe ierr?  Or maybe this should be something the user can decide if they want output or not?  Need to be cautious about this because probably not all fitters will have this information (sort of like for #443), but when available this information might be important.",{},{}
9006,IssuesEvent,2015-06-08 15:13:33+00:00,1953389,stripe/stripe-python,9327224,djhohnstein,856813,stripe,closed,Cannot set Additional Owner's field through API,[],[],3,"I'm currently in the process of migrating to Stripe and I've run into some issues with the Account creation process.

I have a marketplace application where users can sell to other users, in which I create charges and transfers to different user's Stripe accounts. 

Some of these accounts should be able to be Corporate accounts. When they go to fill out the information for their Corporate account however, one of the fields they need to submit is additional owners. When they submit their information to my server, and the server ships the information off to Stripe, Stripe incorrectly interprets the additional_owners attribute of the account's legal_entity as a list of strings instead of a list of dictionaries. Below is a pastebin of a few attempts to show the problem:

Setting the legal_entity hash all at once:
http://pastebin.com/8FtUHucw
Stripe's interpretation:
http://imgur.com/oZ5lG2B

Setting the additional_owners manually:
http://pastebin.com/ryG7A49m

In IRC I was told to report this as a bug by @rfunduk. If you could give me any insight as to why this is happening, that'd be great.

Cheers,
Dwight",{},{}
