9214,IssuesEvent,2015-11-24 15:34:50+00:00,9252533,numenta/nupic,470969,rcrowder,1039191,numenta,closed,Coordinate encoder _orderForCoordinate produces different results on Windows to Linux,[],[],12,"In nupic/tests/unit/nupic/encoders/coordinate_test.py -

In the testEncodeSaturateArea test, with side-by-side single step comparison on Ubuntu and Windows, both generate all the same seed's to send into Random. Based on the 25 coordinates when looping through them in encoder.encodeIntoArray I.e. the encoder _hashCoordinate produces the same MD5 hash codes for the 25 coordinates on Windows and Linux.

In nupic/src/nupic/encoders/coordinate.py -

The first coordinate [-2, -2] produces the same return value from _orderForCoordinate (the rng.getReal64() call). But the second and subsequent calls into _orderForCoordinate returns different values on Windows to Linux. Eventually coming to the assert fail on Windows (0.791666r == 8.0 seen here https://ci.appveyor.com/project/numenta-ci/nupic/branch/master).

I've started looking into the _state changes in the C++ RandomImpl side. But this may just be related to long vs int differences. So could be within SWIG.

The same assert fail can be recreated on Linux if the _hashCoordinate uses (2 ** 32) instead of modding with (2 ** 64). BUT that may be a confusing recreation. So beware!
",{},{}
9217,IssuesEvent,2015-07-17 22:30:21+00:00,9252533,numenta/nupic,1041441,jaredweiss,1039191,numenta,opened,Move registerBuildInRegion call in nupic.engine.__init__ to global scope,[],[],0,"`registerBuildInRegion` needs to be run before any of the methods in `nupic.engine.__init__` are run. Otherwise, if `registerPyRegion` or `unregisterPyRegion` is run before a network is initialized (as would happen if loading a serialized network with regions that conflict with the built ins), `registerBuildInRegion` would either break or not have the proper region in it's list of regions. ",{},{}
