10993,IssuesEvent,2016-04-13 14:09:50+00:00,16316451,GoogleCloudPlatform/gcloud-python,112928,jgeewax,2810941,GoogleCloudPlatform,opened,Policy on the basic CRUD operations,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/GoogleCloudPlatform/gcloud-python/labels/core', 'name': 'core', 'color': 'f7c6c7'}]",[],0,"Seems that we're having some disagreements on what our surfaces should look like. Here's my opinion to start the discussion. I use a ""thing API"" that deals with ""things"". You can replace with ""storage"" and ""bucket"" if it that's easier.

/cc @daspecster @dhermes @tseaver @jonparrott 

### Client pattern

A client handles your credentials and is the pipe to the API.

```python
from gcloud import thing
client = thing.Client()
```

### Instantiate a thing

Create the thing object and eventually save it remotely.

```python
thing = client.thing(parameters)
# ...
thing.save()
```

It's unusual, but perhaps you want to ""load"" a thing from the API by first creating the thing object with the right ID, and then reloading it.

```python
thing = client.thing()
thing.id = 'identifier'
thing.reload()
```

### Get a thing

Give me a thing from the API service.

```python
thing = client.get_thing(identifier)
```

### Update a thing

The same pattern as creating a thing, except I start with a loaded thing.

```python
thing = client.get_thing(identifier)
thing.property = 'new value'
thing.save()
```

### Reload a thing

I have a thing, but I suspect it's changed since I loaded it. I want to make sure what i have is fresh...
```python
thing = client.get_thing(identifier)
# ... some time later ...
thing.reload()
```

### List a bunch of things

I have many things stored and I want to go through all of them.

```python
for thing in client.list_things():
  do_something_with(thing)
```

I have lots of things, but I only want 100 of them. I don't care how many API calls there are.

```python
for thing in client.list_things(limit=100):
  do_something_with(thing)
```

I have lots of things, and I want to control specifically how many API calls I'm making -- I'm on a budget!

```python
for thing in client.list_things(api_call_limit=5):
  do_something_with(thing)
```

### Delete a thing

I have a thing that I loaded, or paged through, and I want to delete it.

```python
thing = client.get_thing(identifier)
thing.delete()
```

I want to delete a thing, but I know it's unique ID.

```python
client.delete_thing(identifier)
```

Technically this could also be done with...

```python
client.thing(identifier).delete()
```

### Related

- #895 
- #1718 
- http://stackoverflow.com/questions/30243687/verify-if-a-topic-exists-based-on-topic-name/32019553#32019553",{},{}
11008,IssuesEvent,2015-06-23 20:50:52+00:00,16316451,GoogleCloudPlatform/gcloud-python,242750,tseaver,2810941,GoogleCloudPlatform,opened,"Implement ""client"" pattern for datastore","[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/GoogleCloudPlatform/gcloud-python/labels/datastore', 'name': 'datastore', 'color': '0052cc'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/GoogleCloudPlatform/gcloud-python/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb'}]",[],0,"Per #861.

Steps:

- [ ] Rename `gcloud.datastore.dataset.Dataset` -> `gcloud.datastore.client.Client`.
- [ ] Unwind `_implicit_environ` usage within client.
- [ ] Update `Client` to handle nesting of batches / transactions over primary connection.
- [ ] Move `gcloud.datastore.api` functions to methods of `Client`.
- [ ] Update domain objects making API requests to hold reference to `client`.
- [ ] Update domain object methods taking `connection` to accept `client`, falling back to `self.client`.
- [ ] Remove remaining `_implicit_environ` usage.",{},{}
