11146,IssuesEvent,2018-02-26 04:46:29+00:00,11852493,GoogleCloudPlatform/compute-image-packages,2177709,azrle,2810941,GoogleCloudPlatform,opened,oslogin breaks OpenSSL setup,[],[],0,"Hi,

The problem has been shown that when we use `getpwent()` with oslogin nss module, SSL setup will be broken after the call.

Here is a simple code to reproduce it.
```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <openssl/evp.h>
#include <pwd.h>

int main() {
    OpenSSL_add_all_algorithms();
    EVP_get_digestbyname(""sha256"") ? printf(""loaded\n"") : printf(""not loaded\n"");

    struct passwd *pw;
    setpwent();
    while ((pw = getpwent()) != 0) {}

    EVP_get_digestbyname(""sha256"") ? printf(""loaded\n"") : printf(""not loaded\n"");
    return 0;
}
```
```
$ gcc test-getpwent.c -lssl -lcrypto -o test-getpwent
$ ./test-getpwent
loaded
not loaded

# after removing oslogin from /etc/nsswitch.conf
$ ./test-getpwent
loaded
loaded
```

After tracking it down, I found that the cause can be the `curl_global_cleanup()` called by `oslogin_utils::HttpGet`.

As `oslogin` communicates with metadata without SSL/TLS, can we clear the `CURL_GLOBAL_SSL` bit when initialize curl so that it will not cleanup OpenSSL things?

A simple test is as follows.
```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <openssl/evp.h>
#include <curl/curl.h>

int main() {
    OpenSSL_add_all_algorithms();
    EVP_get_digestbyname(""sha256"") ? printf(""loaded\n"") : printf(""not loaded\n"");

    curl_global_init(CURL_GLOBAL_ALL & ~CURL_GLOBAL_SSL);
    curl_global_cleanup();

    EVP_get_digestbyname(""sha256"") ? printf(""loaded\n"") : printf(""not loaded\n"");
    return 0;
}
```
```
$ gcc test-curl.c -lssl -lcrypto -lcurl -o test-curl
$ ./test-curl
loaded
loaded
```

Test environment:
```
libcurl3/xenial-updates,xenial-security,now 7.47.0-1ubuntu2.6 amd64 [installed]
libcurl3-gnutls/xenial-updates,xenial-security,now 7.47.0-1ubuntu2.6 amd64 [installed]
libcurl4-openssl-dev/xenial-updates,xenial-security,now 7.47.0-1ubuntu2.6 amd64 [installed]
openssl/xenial-updates,xenial-security,now 1.0.2g-1ubuntu4.10 amd64 [installed]
```

What do you think?

By the way, the original problem was shown when setting up instances via Chef on GCE with Ubuntu 16.04.  Ruby initializes the OpenSSL when requiring `openssl` (`Init_openssl`) and Chef calls `Etc.passwd` somewhere which leads to a runtime error when trying to use openssl again. 
```
FATAL: RuntimeError: cookbook_file[xxxx] (xxx::xxx line N) had an error: RuntimeError: Unsupported digest algorithm (SHA256).
```
",{},{}
11151,IssuesEvent,2018-02-09 21:52:54+00:00,11852493,GoogleCloudPlatform/compute-image-packages,1766378,illfelder,2810941,GoogleCloudPlatform,closed,instance_setup should generate SSH host keys when none are present,[],[],2,"Right now, instance_setup does not correctly handle the case where no SSH host keys are present, failing to generate them and preventing SSH from starting.

Instead, when instance_setup triggers a key (re)generation, it could work this way:

1. If instance_config specifies a list of cipher suites for which to generate host keys, generate that list.
1. Otherwise, if any host keys are present on the system, generate that list.
1. Otherwise, unconditionally generate ed25519, ecdsa, and rsa host keys. Don't generate dsa keys in this case, as they're no longer viewed as secure; for example, Debian 9 no longer generates these keys upon a fresh install.

In terms of evaluating success vs failure, a success would be ""at least one freshly generated host key is created, and no pre-existing host key remains on the system."" If no host keys end up on the disk, it willl be impossible to log in, and if any old host keys remain present, there may be a security issue.

I suggest logging a non-blocking debugging message if any attempted cipher types fail to generate, but this is not inherently a problem by itself.",{},{}
