Nov 13 22:50:36 ip-10-36-16-122.us-west-2.compute.internal etcd[3465]: [etcd] Nov 13 22:50:36.476 INFO      | d0912b5c56ba4a5c93f531bc52dc0850: snapshot of 10058 events at index 170419 completed
```

This isn't the first time that users have reported issues with etcd/fleet on EC2, and not the first time that we've seen issues with nodes under heavy load on EC2 (see #1547).

I think we can work around the etcd issue by:
* Disabling log snapshotting
* Moving the etcd data directory to an instance's ephemeral disk with the `-data-dir` [configuration option](https://github.com/coreos/etcd/blob/master/Documentation/configuration.md#optional)

However, this is still just a workaround. The root issue is likely that we are using an EBS-backed root volume:

```
        ""BlockDeviceMappings"" : [
          {
            ""DeviceName"" : { ""Fn::FindInMap"": [ ""RootDevices"", { ""Ref"": ""EC2VirtualizationType"" }, ""Name"" ] },
            ""Ebs"" : { ""VolumeSize"" : ""100"" }
          }
        ]
```

We made this change because the ephemeral disk (while fast and SSD-backed) is too small. But rolling the devil's dice on EC2 will sometimes net us instances with poor latency, which results in all kinds of trouble. 

Additionally, @johanneswuerbach reports that his instances sometimes crash when the builder is in its post-start: https://www.dropbox.com/s/tzpcbj0viech0oh/Screenshot%202014-11-13%2017.44.24.png?dl=0

This seems in line with these findings. We can format the ephemeral disk on EC2 (see the example from CoreOS [here](https://coreos.com/docs/running-coreos/cloud-providers/ec2/)) and use that for IO-heavy workloads, or we can stop using an EBS volume for the root device and figure out how much disk we really need (is it just builder?) and use an EBS volume just for those services.",{},{}
12607,IssuesEvent,2015-09-02 05:31:56+00:00,11589713,deis/deis,24980,ineu,6117407,deis,opened,Cluster recreation: git push gives weird errors,[],[],0,"Because of my Ceph OSD issues I've recreated cluster from scratch:
- made a backup of database contents
- skipped everything related to Ceph from http://docs.deis.io/en/latest/managing_deis/backing_up_data/ as my RGW didn't work correctly
- deisctl stop platform
- deisctl uninstall platform
- removed all data containers
- deisctl install platform
- deisctl start platform
- restored database backup
- executed http://docs.deis.io/en/latest/managing_deis/backing_up_data/#finishing-up

Everything is up and running, but I cannot really execute `git push`. I receive errors:

```
> $ git push deis HEAD:master                                                                                                                                                       Подсчет объектов: 537, готово.
Delta compression using up to 8 threads.
Сжатие объектов: 100% (280/280), готово.
Запись объектов: 100% (537/537), 75.89 KiB | 0 bytes/s, готово.
Total 537 (delta 263), reused 442 (delta 213)
chown: cannot access ‘/home/git/test.git/build/tmp.pEVJ8klCpJ’: No such file or directory
fatal: Unable to read current working directory: No such file or directory
To ssh://git@deis.staging.cronycle.com:2222/test.git
 ! [remote rejected] HEAD -> master (pre-receive hook declined)
```

and on next push:

```
> $ LANG= git push deis HEAD:master                                                                                                                                                 Counting objects: 537, done.
Delta compression using up to 8 threads.
Compressing objects: 100% (280/280), done.
Writing objects: 100% (537/537), 75.89 KiB | 0 bytes/s, done.
Total 537 (delta 263), reused 442 (delta 213)
-----> Unable to select a buildpack
fatal: Unable to read current working directory: No such file or directory
To ssh://git@deis.staging.cronycle.com:2222/test.git
 ! [remote rejected] HEAD -> master (pre-receive hook declined)
```

There are no '*.git' directories created in /home/git as well. How do I debug this thing?
Also, despite I've removed all data containers, after the new installation in the `osd tree` I've seen my old OSD. Where could it persist?",{},{}
