13689,IssuesEvent,2017-05-05 11:14:28+00:00,33653601,jupyter/notebook,151929,minrk,7388996,jupyter,opened,focus cell on set_next_input,[],[],0,"It would probably be nice if `set_next_input` payloads (e.g. `%load` magic in IPython) caused the newly created cell to be selected. As it is, typically the cell immediately after the new cell is selected, and the user must navigate manually to the previous cell before proceeding. I think most of the time when set_next_input is called the new cell is likely the next one that should be selected/executed and not the one immediately after it.

Since this is an automatic select/focus event in response to an async message, I imagine doing it properly without bounces or annoying people could be tricky. Especially properly handling the event in the case of 'run all', where subsequent cells have been submitted and selected before the set_next_input payload arrives. One option is to only focus the cell if the immediately-following cell is selected (and in command mode). This would catch the ~90% case of running a single cell with shift-enter.",{},{}
