14183,IssuesEvent,2018-01-24 13:57:20+00:00,39858489,juju-solutions/charms.reactive,18071845,xannz,8684561,juju-solutions,opened,Improvement endpoint docs,[],[],0,"@galgalesh It would be nice if the docs concerning the new endpoint implementation could highlight some major changes that affect the behaviour of flags. 

For example:

> These are mainly intended to be used by the interface layer itself, but can be documented as part of the official API that the interface layer exposes. Additionally, the joined flag will be automatically cleared when there are no remote units remaining on any relation, but neither of the other flags will be automatically cleared. 

This is a big difference and is easy to miss in the wall of text. A notification box or some kind of warning would be helpful.



",{},{}
14194,IssuesEvent,2018-04-20 00:09:40+00:00,43328009,NSLS-II/databroker,199813,tacaswell,8700262,NSLS-II,closed,Implement a 'watch' method that yields new documents by polling,[],[],1,"Recall the [zmq-based subscribe PR in bluesky](https://github.com/NSLS-II/bluesky/pull/395) (not to be confused with the zmq-based ""RunEngine as a service""). The RunEngine pushes documents to a central hub which (caches them and) pushes them to consumers over the network:

``` python
for name, doc in subscribe(host):
    do_stuff(name, doc)
```

As a complement to this (as discussed offline), we need:

``` python
for name, doc in db.watch(optional_query_to_narrow_results):
    do_stuff(name, doc)
```

This addresses one of @klauer's concerns with https://github.com/NSLS-II/bluesky/pull/395 : what happens if the user forgets to configure the zmq stuff until after the scan has started? I am personally against a hybrid solution that was once discussed: to pull from databroker to ""catch up"" and then subscribe to pushes from zmq. But I think having a puller is a good idea, and if someone wanted to build a smart hybrid from these two pieces, they could.

Details to be worked out:
- What happens if `db` is receiving documents from more than one RunEngine at a time? Maybe the RunEngine should insert its hostname + process number + Python ojbect id into the RunStart so that the search query can watch RunEngine instance at a time, if needed.
- How frequent to do the polling? Proposal: multiply polling interval 2 if you don't see a new document on the first try; divide by 2 if you do.
",{},{}
