14287,IssuesEvent,2018-08-25 00:44:54+00:00,24043280,sshuttle/sshuttle,14206975,ColeRominger,8774006,sshuttle,closed,not closing sockets,[],[],0,"I am using sshuttle to allow a whitelisted IP to be used as I migrate services.
I am making hundreds of connections an hour over sshuttle.
Each connection is getting closed but the socket is being left in a FIN_WAIT2 state.
These FIN_WAIT2 sockets accumulate until the nofile ulimit is reached.
Sshuttle then crashes without sending a bad exit code to systemd.
Although I am currently running sshuttle as a service this also happens when I run it directly in the foreground or daemonized. 
Although the snippet says the exit code was 1, my service definition should recognize that but it does not.
The service still seems up and something is still listening at my listen address because I can no longer make outgoing connections aka `curl icanhazip.com` until I restart the service manually.
```shell
$ sockstat -P sshuttle | grep FWAIT2 | wc -l
2115
```
```shell
$ cat /etc/systemd/system/sshuttle.service
[Unit]
Description=sshuttle proxy
After=network.target

[Service]
Type=notify
NotifyAccess=all
LimitNOFILE=4096
User=ubuntu
KillMode=process
PIDFile=/home/ubuntu/sshuttle/sshuttle.pid
ExecStart=/usr/local/bin/sshuttle @/home/ubuntu/sshuttle/sshuttle_config
ExecReload=/bin/kill -SIGINT $MAINPID
Restart=on-failure

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target
Alias=sshuttle.service
```
