14553,IssuesEvent,2016-03-12 08:07:18+00:00,26516210,letsencrypt/letsencrypt,911174,strugee,9289019,letsencrypt,opened,Don't prompt to use the existing cert if the RSA key size changed,[],[],0,"I generated a couple Let's Encrypt certs with the default settings. Then I realized that the default RSA key size is 2048, whereas I prefer to be paranoid and use 4096-bit keys. No problem! I just revoked the old certs and went to reissue new ones, passing `--rsa-key-size`.

It was at this point that I got a prompt telling me that I had a certificate with exactly the same domain name on it, and did I want to keep the existing cert? However, the client should have realized that I was telling it to use a different RSA key size, and gone ahead and reissued the cert.

```
% letsencrypt --version                                                                                                  
letsencrypt 0.4.1

% apt-cache policy letsencrypt
letsencrypt:
  Installed: 0.4.1-1~bpo8+1
  Candidate: 0.4.1-1~bpo8+1
  Version table:
 *** 0.4.1-1~bpo8+1 0
        100 http://ftp.us.debian.org/debian/ jessie-backports/main amd64 Packages
        100 /var/lib/dpkg/status
```",{},{}
