14625,IssuesEvent,2017-03-13 18:43:34+00:00,56217288,confluentinc/confluent-kafka-python,24443646,johnrgregg3,9439498,confluentinc,closed,When does Producer.flush() return?,"[{'id': 407409076, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/confluentinc/confluent-kafka-python/labels/librdkafka', 'name': 'librdkafka', 'color': 'f9d0c4', 'default': False}, {'id': 522374380, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/confluentinc/confluent-kafka-python/labels/wait%20info', 'name': 'wait info', 'color': 'fbca04', 'default': False}]",[],10,"I am running:

confluent_kafka.version ('0.9.2', 590080), confluent_kafka.libversion ('0.9.1', 590335)

I have a Producer, and I have a loop wherein I send a single short message followed immediately by a flush(). Since I have not explicitly set batch.num.messages or queue.buffering.max.ms in the config I handed in when I created the Producer, I assume these take their default values (10000 messages and 1000 ms, respectively). That is, if I send a single message, I would assume that it would sit on a queue for 1000 ms (one second), then get sent. Since flush() will block until Producer.len() is 0, I would expect flush to block for this amount of time (one second). In my production code, this is in fact what I see. In a test script, however, I see that flush() returns after about exactly 0.1 seconds, i.e. 100 ms. My config in this situation looks like this (Note that some things are commented out):

```
    conf = {'bootstrap.servers': kafka_broker,
        'group.id': 'mygroup',
#        'debug': 'all',   # dumps stuff to stdout
        'socket.timeout.ms': 3000,
        'socket.max.fails': 1,
        'error_cb': my_kafka_error,
        'stats_cb': my_stats_cb,
        'statistics.interval.ms': 1000,
        'client.id': ""Master_BE_"" + my_ip,
#        'batch.num.messages': 10000,  # default: 10000
#        'queue.buffering.max.ms': 1000, # default: 1000: ""Maximum time, in milliseconds, for buffering data on the producer queue."" I think this means that if anything is being batched, we will send after this amount of time regardless.
        'api.version.request': True,  # request negotiation of the latest features in broker handshake
#        'partition.assignment.strategy': 'range',
        'partition.assignment.strategy': 'roundrobin',
        'default.topic.config': {
            'message.timeout.ms': 3000,   # How long flush() will hang for
            'acks': 1,  # 1: broker at least writes to its own log before ACKing, and we wait for the ACK
            },
#        'session.timeout.ms': 3000,
        }

```

I see that Producer_flush calls Producer_poll0(500) calls rd_kafka_poll(tmout (i.e. 500)) calls rd_kafka_q_serve(timeout_ms) but then things get confusing to me. Although I notice that the confluent client seems to hardcode a timeout to 500 ms, but none of the times I am observing seem to be 500 ms., so there is something else going on.

",{},{}
