14956,IssuesEvent,2016-02-24 11:45:55+00:00,40094312,pyserial/pyserial,530015,msmosso,10537924,pyserial,opened,String being cut when using write() method,[],[],0,"Hi folks,

My string is being cut in the middle of the sentence. Is there any workaround?

```
import serial

port = ""COM1""
ser = serial.Serial(port, 115200, timeout=3)
ser.write('setenv -p F1 ""flash -noheader 127.0.0.1:lalala.kernel flash0.kernel""\r\n')
ser.write('setenv -p F2 ""flash -revend1 127.0.0.1:lelele.ubi nandflash0.rootfs""\r\n')
```

In the above case, the second command stops in 12.

I tried to use ser.flush() after the first write, but it didn't work.
I also tried to use something like ```for i in range (0, len(str)):```, but it doesn't work either.

Thanks in advance,
Cheers!",{},{}
14981,IssuesEvent,2018-04-11 02:17:08+00:00,112676803,apple/turicreate,5673251,znation,10639145,apple,closed,Windows 10 Compability?,[],[],2,"Hi,
I am here to ask about the compatibility of turicreate in windows 10. I've been taking a class that uses turicreate, and I used to own a mac. Then I sold my mac and switched to Windows 10, thinking turicreate would support Windows 10 and I made sure the Linux on Windows option is on. However when I ran pip install -U turicreate(and I made sure pip is updated) it threw me this error:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/27667864/38581931-0c08dc02-3cc3-11e8-8a27-a6931d71c86e.png)
Then I tried fresh windows install in VMWare and got the same error.

What should I do? Or is it because turicreate simply don't support windows? (It should not be... since Graphlab Create supports windows...)


",{},{}
