16223,IssuesEvent,2017-08-22 18:57:32+00:00,43852872,PulpQE/pulp-smash,9053044,kersommoura,14839747,PulpQE,opened,Replace BaseAPITestCase as parent class by unittest.TestCase,"[{'id': 405150856, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/PulpQE/pulp-smash/labels/Issue%20Type:%20Plan', 'name': 'Issue Type: Plan', 'color': 'fef2c0', 'default': False}]",[],0,"
Few tests fail due to time-out that happening during the execution of tear down.
To reduce the number of calls to `client.delete(ORPHANS_PATH)`, and try to reduce the number of failures. Replace the BaseAPITestCase by unittest.TestCase. 
```
    @classmethod
    def tearDownClass(cls):
        """"""Delete all resources named by ``resources``.""""""
        client = api.Client(cls.cfg)
        for resource in cls.resources:
            client.delete(resource)
        client.delete(ORPHANS_PATH)
```

Basically, it will be necessary pass class by class, replace the parent class and do the necessary re-factors.

See also: [#762](https://github.com/PulpQE/pulp-smash/issues/762)",{},{}
16224,IssuesEvent,2015-10-13 17:06:27+00:00,43852872,PulpQE/pulp-smash,1012989,Ichimonji10,14839747,PulpQE,opened,Create and document installable pulp-smash script,[],[],0,"Pulp Smash does not and never will install executable scripts into system-wide locations. That's something for either a package manager or a system administrator to do. That said, there's nothing wrong with providing shell scripts for their use!

Let's create a shell script. It can look like this:

```sh
#!/usr/bin/env sh
python -m pulp_smash ""$@""
```

Let's call this script `pulp-smash`, make it executable, place it somewhere in the `docs` directory and include the script in the documentation. The documentation should note that this script can be copied to `/usr/local/bin/pulp-smash`.

By way of example, consider [this directory](https://github.com/SatelliteQE/nailgun/tree/master/docs). Some shell scripts are placed directly in that file. The scripts are included into the documentation using the `.. literalinclude::` reST directive. See an examle [here](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/SatelliteQE/nailgun/master/docs/examples.rst).",{},{}
