17034,IssuesEvent,2017-09-18 18:34:02+00:00,38581626,pybind/pybind11,4616906,henryiii,17565521,pybind,opened,Buffer object additions,[],[],0,"If you make something a buffer type, this adds the ability to do:
```python
ob_vals = memoryview(ob)
# or
ob_vals = np.fromarray(ob)

ob_vals[:] = 0
# etc.
```

There are a standard set of operations that a buffer object will tend to have. `[]` indexing, length, etc, and they all can be defined with the structure defining the buffer object. Is there a way to set up these standard helper methods? Something like this:

```cpp
.def_buffer([](MyArray &r) -> py::buffer_info {
     return py::buffer_info(
         r.data(),                         // Pointer to buffer
         {static_cast<ssize_t>(r.size())}, // Diminsions
         {sizeof(float)}                   // Strides (in bytes) for each index
         );
    },
   py::buffer_helpers::getitem<1>(), // 1D
   py::buffer_helpers::setitem<1>() // Etc
)
```

These helpers could add things like (based on test_sequences_and_iterators):
* `__getitem__`, with slicing support, following numpy for 2+ D
* `__setitem__`, as above
* `__len__`
* `__iter__`

Some of these are a bit tricky to add manually, and are fully defined by the `buffer_info` struct.

Is something like this practical in pybind11? The operators `py::self` seem to be able to do something like this, and `py::pickle`, but I didn't see a more general extensible mechanism for adding named methods.

As a side note, the shorter, cleaner, less general versions of `py::buffer_info` are not mentioned in the documentation, though they are used in the tests.",{},{}
17050,IssuesEvent,2016-03-06 12:30:31+00:00,38581626,pybind/pybind11,1203629,wjakob,17565521,pybind,closed,Function pointers and placeholders,[],[],0,"Hi, 

First of all, great job with this library, it is really helpful!  I have a small problem with the code below however. I am passing a function which creates a shared pointer in another.

This works fine:

```c++
#include <memory>

#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
#include <pybind11/stl.h>
#include <pybind11/functional.h>

using namespace std;

class Car {
private:
  const int miles;
  const int horses;

public:
  Car(const int miles, const int horses) :miles(miles), horses(horses) {};
  ~Car() {};

  static Car build_car(const int miles, const int horses) {
    return Car(miles, horses);
  };
};

typedef std::function< Car(const int, const int) > car_builder;

class Factory {
private:
  const car_builder builder;
public:
  Factory(const car_builder builder): builder(builder) {};
  ~Factory() {};
};
  

namespace py = pybind11;

PYBIND11_PLUGIN(ok_function) {
    py::module m(""ok_function"", ""ok car plugin"");

    py::class_<Car, shared_ptr<Car> >(m, ""Car"")
      .def(py::init<const int, const int>())
      .def_static(""build_car"",
        &Car::build_car,
        ""Simply construct a car"",
          py::arg(""miles""),
          py::arg(""horses""));

    py::class_<Factory>(m, ""Factory"")
      .def(py::init<const car_builder>()); // <-- WORKS.

    return m.ptr();
}
```

While this:

```c++
#include <memory>

#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
#include <pybind11/stl.h>
#include <pybind11/functional.h>

using namespace std;

class Car {
private:
  const int miles;
  const int horses;

public:
  Car(const int miles, const int horses) :miles(miles), horses(horses) {};
  ~Car() {};

  static shared_ptr<Car> build_car(const int miles, const int horses) {
    return make_shared<Car>(miles, horses);
  };
};

typedef std::function< shared_ptr<Car>(const int, const int) > car_builder;

class Factory {
private:
  const car_builder builder;
public:
  Factory(const car_builder builder): builder(builder) {};
  ~Factory() {};
};
  
namespace py = pybind11;

PYBIND11_DECLARE_HOLDER_TYPE(placeholder, shared_ptr<placeholder>);
PYBIND11_PLUGIN(buggy_function) {
    py::module m(""buggy_function"", ""Buggy car plugin"");

    py::class_<Car, shared_ptr<Car> >(m, ""Car"")
      .def(py::init<const int, const int>())
      .def_static(""build_car"",
        &Car::build_car,
        ""Simply construct a car"",
          py::arg(""miles""),
          py::arg(""horses""));

    py::class_<Factory>(m, ""Factory"")
      .def(py::init<const car_builder>()); // <-- DOES NOT WORK.

    return m.ptr();
}
```

... does not compile. I get the error:

```
/usr/local/include/pybind11/cast.h: In instantiation of ‘T pybind11::cast(pybind11::handle) [with T = std::shared_ptr<Car>]’:
/usr/local/include/pybind11/cast.h:579:85:   required from ‘T pybind11::handle::cast() const [with T = std::shared_ptr<Car>]’
