17053,IssuesEvent,2016-04-11 16:13:13+00:00,38581626,pybind/pybind11,1203629,wjakob,17565521,pybind,closed,Virtual function dispatch has problems with similar-named functions,[],[],0,"I am unable to call a virtual function (implemented in python) from that virtual function in another object. It looks like there is code in `get_overload` that compares function names and returns a null function if it matches. I suppose this was added to prevent infinite looping (?), but results in false positives.

Small example: Cpp File:

    #include <iostream>
    #include <pybind11/pybind11.h>

    struct Base {
        virtual void Print(void) const = 0;
    };
    
    struct PyClass {

        virtual void Print(void) const {
            PYBIND11_OVERLOAD_PURE(
                void,
                Base,
                Print
            );
        }
    };
    
    void CallPrint(const Base * b) { b->Print(); }

    PYBIND11_PLUGIN(mytest)
    {
        pybind11::module m(""mytest"", ""A test"");

        pybind11::class_<PyClass> base(m, ""Base"");
        base.alias<Base>()
            .def(pybind11::init<>())
            .def(""Print"", &Base::Print);

        m.def(""CallPrint"", &CallPrint);

        return m.ptr();
    }


Python:

    import mytest as my

    class PyClass1(my.Base):
      def __init__(self):
        my.Base.__init__(self)

      def Print(self):
        print(""In PyClass1"")


    class PyClass2(my.Base):
      def __init__(self):
        my.Base.__init__(self)

      def Print(self):
        print(""In PyClass2"")
        p = PyClass1()
        my.CallPrint(p)  # <<< Problem here

    b = PyClass2()
    my.CallPrint(b)
                                          

Error is `RuntimeError: Tried to call pure virtual function ""Print""`",{},{}
17056,IssuesEvent,2016-10-14 01:08:16+00:00,38581626,pybind/pybind11,1562730,hersh,17565521,pybind,opened,Is it possible to see C++ subclass info from an object that returns a superclass pointer?,[],[],0,"I'm trying to write something that has a narrow interface like a getter that returns a superclass pointer, and I would like to return various subclass instances through that and then have the python code figure out which type the instance is.

I don't see how to do this with pybind11 currently, and I've read the docs through quite a few times.  Is it possible to do what I'm trying?

Thanks for a great product, by the way, I've gotten a lot of great use out of it.

Here is my current attempt.

C++:

```
// compile with:
// g++ -fPIC -shared -std=c++11 -I$HOME/pybind11/include `python-config --cflags --ldflags` subclassinfo.cpp -o subclassinfo.so

#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>

struct Super
{
  int a;
};

struct Sub: public Super
{
  int b;
};

class Source
{
public:
  std::shared_ptr<Super> get()
    {
      Sub* sub = new Sub;
      sub->a = 1;
      sub->b = 2;
      return std::shared_ptr<Super>(sub);
    }
};

namespace py = pybind11;

PYBIND11_DECLARE_HOLDER_TYPE(T, std::shared_ptr<T>);

PYBIND11_PLUGIN(subclassinfo)
{
  py::module m(""subclassinfo"", ""test of subclass info"");

  py::class_<Super, std::shared_ptr<Super> > super(m, ""Super"");
  super.def_readwrite(""a"", &Super::a);

  py::class_<Sub, std::shared_ptr<Sub> >(m, ""Sub"", super)
    .def_readwrite(""b"", &Sub::b);

  py::class_<Source>(m, ""Source"")
    .def(py::init<>())
    .def(""get"", &Source::get, py::return_value_policy::reference_internal);

  return m.ptr();
}
```

Python:

```
#!/usr/bin/python

import subclassinfo

source = subclassinfo.Source()
obj = source.get()
print obj.a
print obj.b
```

Python thinks the returned object is a Super, so it fails when I try to print obj.b:

```
hersh@chubs$ python subclassinfo.py
1
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""subclassinfo.py"", line 8, in <module>
    print obj.b
AttributeError: 'subclassinfo.Super' object has no attribute 'b'
```",{},{}
