18094,IssuesEvent,2018-08-15 05:50:59+00:00,35531022,opendatacube/datacube-core,37929162,mergify[bot],26125288,opendatacube,closed,No way to create `MetadataType` without database connection,"[{'id': 210910444, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWwyMTA5MTA0NDQ=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/opendatacube/datacube-core/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb', 'default': True}, {'id': 544129361, 'node_id': 'MDU6TGFiZWw1NDQxMjkzNjE=', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/opendatacube/datacube-core/labels/improvement%20proposal', 'name': 'improvement proposal', 'color': '1d76db', 'default': False}]",[],2,"In order to construct `MetadataType` object from yaml definition one has to have access to connected db index. No information is queried from the DB during construction. It's just that `doc->MetadataType` conversion is part of the index api attached to an `index` object

```python
m = dc.index.metadata_types.from_doc(doc)
```

`MetadataType` class is just a container of ""dataset search fields"", the type of the search fields will be different for different index implementations, but there is nothing that depends on the state stored inside the db. 

I propose that 

- Database index driver should expose constructor method for `MetadataType`
- We should have ""dataset search fields"" implementation that is not tied to any DB driver

If I have ""metadata definition yaml"" and ""dataset yaml"" I should be able to parse ""dataset yaml"" according to ""metadata definition yaml"" without connecting to the database, and even without deciding what db index should be used.

I believe this limitation is impacting testing in a negative way, a lot of the tests that could have been ""unit tests"" are now forced into ""integration test"" category, and integration tests are harder to write and are slower to run.

 ",{},{}
18120,IssuesEvent,2018-03-29 00:02:24+00:00,126552353,python-trio/outcome,609896,njsmith,26335827,python-trio,opened,Support **kwargs in capture/acapture?,[],[],0,"I left this out of the original version of this code because in general in trio this is a complicated issue (https://github.com/python-trio/trio/issues/470), and I figured it was better to be consistent with other trio functions like `trio.run`, where we need to reserve kwargs for controlling the parent function. But now that it's a separate library, that doesn't really apply. And `capture` and `acapture` are obviously complete as they stand; there's no way we'll ever want to add any other arguments to them.",{},{}
18123,IssuesEvent,2018-02-11 17:28:03+00:00,60112633,python-trio/async_generator,42327,pquentin,26335827,python-trio,opened,Unexpected RuntimeError: partially-exhausted async_generator garbage collected,[],[],0,"async_generator is really useful! But I see one surprising behavior. When I run this code:

```python3
import trio
from async_generator import async_generator, yield_


@async_generator
async def items():
    for i in range(10):
        await yield_(i)


async def main():
    async for i in items():
        if i > 4:
            break
        print(i)


if __name__ == '__main__':
    trio.run(main)
```

I get the following exception:

```
Exception ignored in: <bound method AsyncGenerator.__del__ of <async_generator._impl.AsyncGenerator object at 0x110a9b908>>
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "".../python3.5/site-packages/async_generator/_impl.py"", line 324, in __del__
    .format(self._coroutine.cr_frame.f_code.co_name)
RuntimeError: partially-exhausted async_generator 'items' garbage collected
```

Is this expected? The same code using the Python 3.6 syntax does not print any exception. Thanks!",{},{}
